<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-836  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 836.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  Nov 1989 v77 n11 p1695(14).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The use of satellite technology for oceanic air traffic control.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Massoglia, Peter L.; Pozesky, Martin T.; Germana, Guy T.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Use of satellite communications to control aircraft flying overoceans is discussed.andP;  The International Civil AviationOrganization (ICAO) provides air traffic services over large areasof the Atlantic and Pacific oceans and differs considerably fromthe system used in the contiguous US.andP;  Aircraft in domesticairspace are illuminated by radar once every 12 seconds, and radiocommunication is more frequent.andP;  Oceanic airspace is monitored viahigh-frequency radio channels, which are easily affected byionospheric propagation conditions and electrical storms.andP;  Thecleared flight plan (clearance) and the pilot-reported position(progress report) are used to track oceanic aircraft.andP;  The ICAOFuture Air Navigation Systems Committee was formed in 1983 tostudy, identify and assess new air navigation techniques,including space-based radar, cooperative independent surveillanceand automatic dependent surveillance.andP;  Their work is described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Air Traffic ControlControl SystemsSatellite CommunicationsFuture TechnologiesResearch and DevelopmentNavigationInternational Civil Aviation Organization.andO;Feature:   illustrationmapchart.andO;Caption:   US oceanic flight information regions. (map)Cleared flight plan example. (chart)Typical oceanic flight strip. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>